=====================================================================================
  THE VERDICT
=====================================================================================

  Career BRAVS:     36.8
  Career WAR-eq:    22.9
  Career Era-Std:   34.8
  Peak season:      11.7 BRAVS (2017)
  Peak 5 seasons:   43.4 BRAVS
  HR total:         454

  HOF COMPARISON (typical career WAR-eq thresholds):

    Clear HOFer:       50+ WAR-eq
    Borderline:        35-50 WAR-eq
    Hall of Very Good: 25-35 WAR-eq
    Below threshold:   <25 WAR-eq

  Stanton at 22.9 WAR-eq is below typical HOF thresholds.

  THE CASE FOR:
    - 454 career HR (approaching milestones)
    - MVP season: 11.7 BRAVS in 2017
    - 7 seasons above 3.0 BRAVS (solid value)
    - Top 3 seasons averaged 9.8 BRAVS (strong peak)

  THE CASE AGAINST:
    - 5 seasons with <100 games played (durability)
    - 7 negative-BRAVS seasons (injuries + decline)
    - DH penalty: spent significant time at DH (-17.5 runs/162)
    - Averaged only 102 games/season over career
    - 11 of 17 seasons with <120 games

  BRAVS VERDICT: NO -- below HOF threshold, though HR milestones may help with voters

  CONTEXT: Stanton's case mirrors the broader HOF debate about
  peak vs. longevity. His best seasons (MVP year, 59 HR in 2017)
  are genuinely elite. But chronic injuries have stolen hundreds
  of games from his career, and the shift to DH has eliminated
  any defensive value. BRAVS penalizes both of these — durability
  losses and the DH positional penalty are explicit components.

  If Stanton reaches 500 HR, voters will struggle to keep him out
  regardless of what any metric says. But by BRAVS's cold
  probabilistic accounting, his career value is well below HOF standards despite the power numbers.

